Today we're going to review the main camera movements used in film and we're going to teach them [Music]. Camera movements are one of the ways the camera narrates and conveys information. They have different names and ways of categorizing, but for this occasion, we're going to separate them into physical movements with displacement and physical movements without displacement on the one hand, and optical movements on the other. Let's start with physical movements without displacement. The first is the pan. The pan is a horizontal movement with the camera mounted on an axis, usually a tripod, and it goes from left to right or vice versa. It causes an effect very similar to turning your head and is often used to follow a character or to show a place and allow the viewer to appreciate everything. It's also a good way to generate suspense because it allows us to hear or perceive something on the way to showing it. A variant of the pan is the sweep. It's the same but faster. This adds dynamism and adrenaline because it conveys a certain urgency. It's also often used as a transition between scenes. Another movement is the tilt, which works like the pan but vertically, with the camera mounted on the tripod. We move up or down.  The movement of looking up or down is often used to accompany a character's gaze or to introduce them gradually. It's also a very common way to begin a story with a shot descending from the sky, or vice versa, to end it. The last of the physical movements without displacement is the roll. It's the most complex and least natural of this group because it's the only movement that doesn't resemble any we can make with our head. It's when the camera rotates on its own axis, ending up upside down. A very symbolic movement that can have different narrative uses. While it can be done manually, the smoothest way is using a stabilizer, which, among its many functions, includes roll. Now we move on to physical movements with displacement, and to start, we'll talk about the tracking shot. The tracking shot consists of moving the camera in a direction. It can be a forward tracking shot, a backward tracking shot, an up-and-down tracking shot, a circular tracking shot, or a tracking shot. The tracking shot has many narrative uses and can be done in different ways, from a wheelchair to a stabilizer and a very steady hand, but the most effective is the tracking dolly, which consists of rails on which a platform runs, on which the camera equipment is mounted to bring the camera to the camera.  For very short links, a very ingenious tripod attachment called a white track is often used. The up-and-down tracking shot is usually done with a crane, also known as a boom. It's called a tracking shot when the movement follows a specific character or object. This is true regardless of the type or combination of tracking shots used. The remaining physical movement without displacement is the random shake or handheld camera, which is when the camera moves freely or without much stability. It's often used in action sequences because it adds a lot of chaos to the scene, especially when it's not used all the time due to the contrast with the calm of stabilized shots. Now it's time for optical movements, which are those that have to do with what happens with the camera lenses and the effects they produce. Zoom in and zoom out is a way to get closer to and further away from the characters. It was much more intimate than a tracking shot since the background reacts differently than the object in focus, blurring or becoming sharper. And just as panning is a faster version of panning, the fast version of zooming is called crafting, which serves to emphasize something very strongly. The other major optical movement is the  Rack focus allows us to use focus narratively, directing attention within the frame to one thing or another. Cinema makes narrative use of all these effects, mixing and combining them, sometimes fusing them to generate different effects. The clearest example of this is the training ground or the Hitchcockian show, since its first recognized use was in Alfred Hitchcock's Vertigo. And that's all for today. Leave your comments about this favorite camera movement. If you liked it, don't forget to give us a like, subscribe to the channel, and turn on notifications so you're notified when we upload new videos. We'll be uploading reviews, tips, and lots of other super useful things. [Music]

