When we see a shot that we like, it is the result of the combination of several factors and how the elements in the frame are organized, this is what we refer to when we talk about composition. There are many elements to consider when composing a shot and several ways in which it can be done. Therefore, since the methods and possibilities are really very broad, in this video we are going to concentrate on those that are seen more frequently, and although everything we're going to talk about is applicable to still photography and painting, since this is an audiovisual channel, I am only going to focus on those issues that are also applicable to film and series, but in any case, I think you will get a fairly solid foundation. Composition is an art, and as such, its appreciation is subjective, but based on elements and common patterns through which humans perceive images, there are some guidelines that it is good to know and take into account to know how a shot is structured and balanced to convey a certain idea or feeling. Without a doubt, one of the most commonly used methods is the principle of figure-ground relationship established by Gestalt psychology, which states that, when attention is focused on an element, the image is conceptually separated into a background and a figure. The latter being what you want to highlight, the center of interest, which can be an object, a person, or a part of the person. However, if the situation were reversed and attention was paid to what was previously the background, it would become the figure, as can happen when there is, for example, a change of focus. By the way, there is another similar division to figure and background that can be made under the name of "positive space", to refer to the point of interest, and "negative space", to refer to everything surrounding the point of interest within the frame. Sometimes the negative space is expanded to give less room in the frame to the subject matter, to convey a sense of loneliness, isolation, or calm through the image. Our Western eyes, being accustomed to reading and decoding from left to right, if the character is composed to the left and to their right there is a lot of negative space, the frame can suggest that they have a long way to go. On the contrary, it can mean that they have already traveled it if this is reversed and the character is situated on the right side of the frame. So, before starting to compose, it is fundamental to know what the point of interest in the image will be, you need to know who or what will be the protagonist(s) of the frame. Some of the elements you can play with when composing are: Attracting attention to a specific center of interest, the texture and tactile sensations that the image can evoke, the shape and volume of objects, as well as the sense of depth of these in the scene, or the contrast, whether by tone, size, theme, or some other element. There are elements of an image that help capture attention or convey the intended message. One can draw the viewer's gaze to a specific area of the frame by using essentially colors, sizes, and locations. But to understand these elements, it is necessary to know through which means they can be highlighted and how they function in relation to human perception. For that, we have: focus, framing, the placement of objects within the frame, and the lighting and colors of the scene. These are the four main sections that will structure this video. Focus is one of the most basic elements when it comes to directing the viewer's gaze to where you want it, and it can be divided into two main groups: selective focus and total focus. In selective focus, the subject is in focus while the background is out of focus, which allows highlighting and concentrating the attention on a specific part of the image. And total focus is as simple as it sounds, referring to when everything in the image is in focus, both subject and background. While this removes the possibility of drawing attention through focus, it is often used for wide shots, like landscapes, where capturing all details sharply is desired. In this section, we will talk about some small considerations and issues that are usually taken into account when choosing how to position the camera. For the subject matter to be the center of attention, it is very common to have it occupy most of the space in the composition, known as "filling the frame". This helps to eliminate possible distracting elements and prevents the subject matter from losing prominence if too many elements are included in the composition. Using what is known as "frame within a frame" is another way to highlight a point of interest by framing it with some border. These can be more pronounced or more subtle, and are generally used with doors, windows, or even natural elements, but anything that isolates the subject from the rest of the frame will serve to highlight it, draw the viewer's attention to it, and increase the sense of depth of the image. In cases where there is a visually very static frame, to avoid an undesired flat and two-dimensional appearance, it is advisable to enhance the sense of physical depth of the scene, and this can be achieved by adding objects in the foreground, middle ground, and background of the composition. This sense of depth can also be generated by using marked vanishing points, for which we will need "leading lines". These are the dominant lines that may be present in a composition, which can be physically marked lines or suggested lines that are not so clearly defined. They are a powerful ally when it comes to directing the viewer’s attention. If the lines are repeated, the effect is reinforced, but at the same time, it becomes more evident as a resource. Horizontal lines convey feelings of stability, calm, or rest, as they seem to rest on a surface. Vertical lines convey strength, power, or growth, and diagonal lines help to create a dynamic image and can be divided into two main types: ascending, which according to the context can metaphorically convey a sense of effort, slowness, or progress, or, on the contrary, descending, as if the character were falling down a ramp, which can convey a sense of speed or decline. Diagonal lines can also be ideal for creating depth in compositions, especially if they are convergent, meaning when due to the effect of distance they seem to converge towards a single point, like train tracks. Curved lines, especially "S" shapes, are also very appealing to the eye because they have a more erratic structure and invite the eye to follow them. A basic case of a dominant line is the horizon line; keeping it straight and horizontal is usually a key visual reference for maintaining a stable image. But this can be broken with what is known as a "Dutch angle", a concept referring to a tilted frame. Depending on the context, it can convey dynamism, unease, or sometimes even be used symbolically, although it is advisable not to overuse this technique to avoid overdoing it and ending up with a movie like Battlefield Earth. Now we move on to the most fundamental part of composition, which is how and where to place the elements. This is probably the longest section of the video because there are various composition criteria that can be used and many elements to take into account. Returning to the horizon, intuitively one might think that the logical thing would be to place it in the center of the image, however, it is recommended to place it in a third, either the lower or upper third, of the image, because this way you choose and prioritize the sky or the ground as the background or even as the subject of the image. On the other hand, if you place the horizon in the middle, it is unclear which of the two should be highlighted, as both the ground and the sky occupy the same space in the frame. This is related to the fact that, to highlight the point of interest and guide the viewer's gaze towards it, the most common option is to have the point of interest dominate the frame while ensuring that other objects do not draw more attention than it does. For this reason, and to avoid discomfort to the eye, it is also usually avoided to have one subject matter obscure another. It is important to note that while the main focus is on the placement of the essential part of the object, like the face of a character, other directions marked by the rest of the body or objects, as well as other elements or characters that have certain prominence in the composition, are also important for the composition. But once you have an idea of what the point of interest is how do you know where to place it? For this, some concepts are usually applied such as the "rule of the gaze," which states that if the character or even the object is placed at one end of the frame and is looking in that same direction, let's say to the left, the space on the right loses importance and leaves an unbalanced composition with too much weight on the left and too little on the right. If, on the other hand, the character or object is on one side of the frame but is looking towards the opposite side, the framing gives importance to the space in front of the character, which is important since that's where they are looking and where their interest is focused, so it's more relevant to see the space in front of them than the empty space behind them, resulting in a more balanced composition. Thus, the rule of the gaze states that, depending on where the character is looking, the frame should have one third of the space behind them and two-thirds in front. And if we're talking about video, it's worth noting that often the character or object is followed, even when they turn or change direction, to maintain this composition. But understanding this is no guarantee of a good frame, and it’s not very useful if you don’t know how high or low to place the point of interest, just as the rule of thirds helps balance the image horizontally, headroom is a criterion that can help balance it vertically. Headroom is the space between the top of the frame and the head of the character or object, the amount of space considered appropriate varies depending on the size of the shot and the figure, but the idea is to not leave too much space or too little, as a general reference, the eyes are usually placed one-third below the top edge of the frame. With a balanced composition horizontally and vertically, you ensure having a good amount and well-balanced negative space, while giving the image and the viewer room to breathe, avoiding an undesirable feeling of confinement. The guidelines for leaving enough space above and to the sides of the image may seem a bit intuitive and inexact, but luckily to help simplify and organize this, there is the most commonly used technique of all, especially in cinema, which is "the rule of thirds" and it’s the first method we will see for composition. The rule of thirds is a visual composition technique designed to create a balanced and pleasing image to the eye, avoiding the point of interest splitting the image in half or being in the center of the frame, giving a sense of symmetry that is not intended. This technique consists of dividing the frame into three equal vertical thirds and three horizontal thirds, thus creating nine rectangles of the same size and four intersection points. On these lines, and especially at the intersection points, is where we should place what we want to highlight in the image. In case of having two centers of interest, they are usually placed each at an intersection point and ideally diagonally, to distribute the weight evenly between the lower and upper halves of the composition. It can also be possible to group two or more centers of interest and treat them as one when composing the frame. However, it should be noted that these lines are guides, and while it's necessary for the character or object to be relatively close, it doesn’t need to be perfectly on the line because, since the viewer doesn’t have a grid of thirds marked with precision on their retina, everything becomes a matter of relative perception. However, some consider that the structure of the rule of thirds is too stable and static, which is why they choose to use another composition criterion called "dynamic symmetry," for which you first draw a line between the corners of the frame, and then intersect it with a perpendicular line, that is, at 90 degrees, connecting it with a corner of the frame. The result, like with the rule of thirds, is a point of interest at the intersection of both lines. By doing the same with the remaining corner, you get a new point of interest, and then it's a matter of repeating the same operation with the opposite main diagonal, thus obtaining the 4 key points of the image. The points of interest are slightly shifted in relation to the points obtained from the rule of thirds, but the main difference is in the lines, as they are not as perfect and stable, and by relying entirely on diagonal directions, they attract more attention, better mark the perspective, and are more dynamic in indicating the direction of the elements in the composition. Very briefly touching on other compositional methods, there's also the "golden composition," created from a pattern of numbers and measurements based on the golden spiral or Fibonacci spiral, which is associated with a beautiful image and can be found in various objects in nature. However, since the rule of thirds is a simplification of the golden ratio, unless you follow the Fibonacci spiral pattern very strictly, broadly speaking, the truth is that the golden composition usually doesn’t yield very different results or ones that cannot be achieved through the rule of thirds. Another method is the "rule of odds," having a single element in the image can convey a sense of loneliness or isolation, and two elements can create a composition that is too balanced and static, where both have almost identical weight and neither stands out over the other, but if there are three elements, a center is created among them. A greater number of even elements can be complicated to distribute, as it will always be a divisible number and thus the brain will probably form patterns and segmentation, providing an image that is divided and conceptually organized in a way the creator might not want, whereas if the number of elements remains odd, even if it is more than 3, this conceptual division won't happen and the image will look a bit more organic. And now let's move on to the last compositional method we will see: symmetry. The different methods of composition, including symmetry, can be used in various ways. For example, while Wes Anderson keeps it present throughout the entire film and uses it as an aesthetic and stylistic resource, Kubrick chooses to use it only for those shots that are prominent for the story. One of the studies developed by Gestalt psychology talks about the principle of symmetry, which states that the human mind finds a symmetrical image more attractive and balanced. This is enhanced if the motifs placed on both sides of the axis of symmetry have the same visual weight, and if the composition is centered around a vanishing point, even better. But, even if a symmetrical composition is not being used, it may be necessary to place the object of interest in the center anyway. This applies especially to video because it may be necessary for the viewer's eye to find the point of interest almost immediately without having to search for it in the frame, so the viewer will always have what they need to see right in front of their eyes. This allows for creating a fast and dynamic montage that is easy to understand and where the viewer's eye doesn't have to jump from side to side following the point of interest, because it will always be right in the center. Examples of this are the montage sequences by Edgar Wright, and even Mad Max: Fury Road follows this criterion throughout almost the entire film. The principle of symmetry shows us that the mind always wants to find visual balance, especially to understand how important balance and proportion are in distributing the elements in the composition. And so now we move on to talk about the different factors that influence whether an element has more or less weight within the frame. If a point of interest is too far from other elements in the frame, it can leave an empty space in the scene. In that case, one option is to balance the image with other objects filling the space or air that is creating that unwanted feeling of emptiness. On the other hand, it can also happen that another element in the image is attracting more attention than necessary, diminishing the subject matter a bit. That's when the composition's weight should be balanced so that the desired point of interest has the strength and presence it needs to stand out in the frame. Balancing the weight of an image has to do with the attention that each of the elements in the composition attracts. Although it must be remembered that compositional balance is something relative, these are some of the elements that influence the visual weight of objects: Light elements on a dark background weigh more than dark elements on a light background. Against a uniform background, the tone that contrasts the most with the background color will be heavier. Warm colors weigh more than cool colors. The larger the size, the heavier the object in the image and, consequently, it will attract more attention, and as an extra, size can also demonstrate in a shot a power relationship between characters, either to show that one has superiority over another or to show equality. But nevertheless, Not all composition schemes are based on the figure-ground relationship, the psychologist Rudolf Arnheim distinguished four different methods of composition: central, binary, hierarchical, and atonal. The central ones have a single strong point, this is the scheme most similar to figure-ground and can refer to something as simple as a portrait. Binary schemes present a duo of figures or groups and are typical of symmetric compositions. In atonal schemes, we can find many elements of equal weight that homogenize to create a unit centered on texture. And finally, hierarchical schemes are constituted by accents that range from strong to weak, related in a subordinate way. As we mentioned earlier, Gestalt psychologists studied minutely the different stimuli that create sensations and perception in the mind, thus forming the so-called "Principles of perception" which, in addition to the figure-ground law and the symmetry law that we mentioned earlier, here are some other Gestalt laws: Principle of proximity, which says that the mind perceptually groups elements that remain close to each other. Principle of continuity, where elements that are grouped continuously, whether straight or curved lines, tend to be perceived as a unit. Principle of identity or similarity, where elements are grouped by analogous characteristics, that is, based for example on color, size, shape, or other visual elements. And it's worth noting that in all these cases repetition is a fundamental unifying element that is attractive to the eye, as our brain often tends to want to group by finding patterns. And now we go to the last section of this video, which is "Lighting and Color." The different types of lights and colors can produce various shadows and shades affecting perception. To address lighting and colors from a composition aspect, it's necessary to know that these can be used to highlight a point of interest. Color is also used to achieve a harmonious image, for this it's advisable to simplify the composition, look for uniform backgrounds, and not use too many very marked colors to avoid backgrounds full of details that can distract attention. In general an image with few elements and few very contrasting colors is more impactful, than a composition with many elements where none stand out from the rest. The black and white image helps to better highlight the contrasts and prevents the color from distracting from other elements, like shape or texture. Saturated colors evoke intensity and soft tones, tranquility. The amount of colors and their range also affect the perception and sensations of the viewer, because each color can evoke specific feelings based on what is called "color psychology," but that's another topic I might cover in a future video. We can distinguish different types of contrasts, some of the most used are: Tone contrast, where saturated or intense colors are combined, with the contrast increasing the further apart the colors are on the color wheel, creating a striking and energetic effect. A subset of tone contrast is complementary color contrast, where this becomes more specific by juxtaposing two diametrically opposed colors on the color wheel. Temperature contrast, which occurs when a warm color is paired with a cool color. And while for the types of contrast just mentioned greater color saturation maximizes the effect of the contrast, one can also opt for "saturation contrast," where vivid colors are set against muted ones. And another type of contrast is brightness or chiaroscuro contrast, which occurs when a dark color is paired with a light one. In these cases, we usually say that the image has "high contrast," thus guiding attention through the juxtaposition of dark and light areas. It should be noted that this type of contrast is independent of color, so it works even in black and white images. And these are the basic (and some not so basic) principles of composition applied to cinema. As you can see, there are many things to keep in mind and, in the best cases, many of these elements manage to combine simultaneously to achieve a composition rich on various levels. And finally, considering that in video, the camera position can be changed at any time during the shot, this gives cinema and series a new possibility that no other (visual) art has, which is that the composition evolves over time. In this way, framing is generated along the shot itself, From very small things, like a slight camera movement, to sequence shots where the camera usually moves constantly, the framing changes. It can even happen that as a shot progresses, the composition criteria need to be changed if required. An example of this is Spielberg's sequence shots, which usually include clearly differentiated compositions. And now that you know all this, looking for and observing these aspects is a great way to rewatch a film you already know, to train your eye by paying attention to all these details and, who knows, maybe even putting them into practice yourself. Although many of the concepts we've seen are presented as "laws" or "rules," it's not mandatory to follow them, in fact, some of the best cinematographers in history often choose not to, mainly because experimentation is essential to discovering new possibilities, and besides, all this applies to achieving a balanced composition that's pleasant to view, pleasant to view, but what about when you want to create a different or more unsettling effect for the viewer through composition and move away from the tranquility of a balanced image? Well, for that, you'll have to wait for the next video where we'll see how these patterns can be broken by analyzing the compositions in Mr. Robot. So if you don't want to miss it, I suggest you subscribe and turn on notifications if you haven't already. As always, thank you very much and see you in the next video.

